<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="563" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1186,2041]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,153,251]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="563" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1942,1968]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species occurs in two forms, one with hind wings well developed (macropterous) and another with hind wings absent (brachypterous). These forms differ morphologically as indicated in the genus description as far as the structure of the forewings and the thorax are concerned. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2019" box="[920,1074,2014,2040]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudindicus">
<emphasis box="[920,1074,2014,2040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">D. sudindicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles the sympatric 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,280,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[151,280,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="563">D. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in being more slender and longer in addition to the characters of the male genitalia. This species is unique among the known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1916" box="[643,771,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[643,771,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="563">Daimachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having triangular projections on both dorsal and ventral surfaces of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
